CQDs have attracted a lot of attention as candidate materials for biosensing and cellular imaging. There are many preparation methods, which can be divided into two preparation methods according to the relationship between carbon source and product: “top-down” and “bottom-up"(Fig. 2
                     ). Purification methods include electrophoresis, centrifugation, dialysis, and column chromatography. Table 1
                      provides an overview of various CQD synthesis and purification methods from various precursors, sizes, and optical characteristics.

CQDs have been widely used in the analysis and detection of environmental, pharmaceutical, clinical, and food fields due to the advantages of low dosage, low detection limit, wide linear range, simple operation, responsive response, as well as precise and trustworthy outcomes. The carbon quantum dot sensor can be built based on changes in the carbon dots' fluorescence intensity. The enhancement or quenching of the fluorescence of the carbon dots may be caused by the functional groups on the surface of the carbon dots through electron transfer, complex formation, or dynamic collision with the analyte [132]. Up to now, CQDs have been used to detect metal ions(K+, A13+, Cr6+, Hg+, Fe3+), anions (Br-,S3-phosphate (Pi), ONOO-), drug molecules (tetracycline, antibiotics, oxytetracycline, methotrexate), biomolecules (DNA,Protein, cholesterol, heme, cysteine (Cys)) bacteria, pH, fingerprints, etc.(Fig. 5
                        ). Table 2
                         summarizes the application of different CQDs in detection.
